Fancy image description

Notes on the data: Costs include all construction and construction-related expenditures, but not rolling stock or sales taxes. In some cases, rolling stock costs are included in the headline numbers, and we have tried to subtract them whenever possible; in some remaining cases, it was not possible, and we note that the costs include the equipment.

  • Costs are adjusted for purchasing power parity (PPP), based on the midpoint of construction. This adjustment is imperfect in countries with rapid changes in the PPP rate due to high inflation, typically in the developing world. Of note, we have not adjusted for inflation so far; since all costs are converted to US dollars, you can inflation-adjust using American inflation rates.
  • The length of a project includes length in service, excluding non-revenue tracks toward railyards and tail tracks; for example, our length for the 7 extensions in New York starts at Times Square and ends at 34th Street and 11th Avenue, even though storage tracks extend south to 26th Street.
  • The source column describes what type of source we used. Often, we used different sources for length and cost, since costs can run over and therefore, we’ve attempted to use the most recent sources possible, whereas length is fixed for the duration of the project.
  1. Wiki means Wikipedia; it is not an acceptable source for costs, only length and opening year.
  2. Measured means we measured the length (including tunnel length) on satellite photos or mapping software like Google Earth or Open Railway Map.
  3. Media means general media.
  4. Trade means trade publications, like Railway Gazette and International Rail Journal.
  5. Plan means official plans, whether by the relevant agency, the state, the World Bank, etc.

About Transit-infrastructure project data set:

Transit-infrastructure project database that spans more than 50 countries and totals more than 11,000 km of urban rail built since the late 1990s. The goal of this dataset is to figure out how to deliver more high-capacity transit projects for a fraction of the cost in countries like the United States.

Purpose of this project:

The main purpose of this project is to visualize subsets of the data to help the reader better understand the nature of the variables presented. We have considered not to make any changes to the original data, however we have done quite a few sub-setting and used some functions to get the particular data that we wanted to visualize and get insights from them. All these steps are well explained along with the flow of the project. This project brings out the presentation to nature of different variables of the data set using 9 different graphs with the help of ggplot2 package.

Transit cost is the data set taken from the mentioned link

transit_cost <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2021/2021-01-05/transit_cost.csv')

Cleaning code-Provided By the Creators.

transit_cost <-transit_cost %>%
  mutate(start_year = as.integer(start_year),
         end_year = as.integer(end_year),
         tunnel_per = parse_number(tunnel_per)/100,
         real_cost = as.numeric(real_cost))

raw_df <- transit_cost %>% 
  janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  filter(real_cost != "MAX")

raw_df %>% 
  arrange(desc(cost_km_millions))



We have used the variables end_year and start_year to calculate the total time taken by the project to complete as a variable -Project_time.

Project_time <- (raw_df$end_year) - (raw_df$start_year)
raw_df$project_time <- Project_time


We have used ggplot2 package for plotting and used histogram geometry for our continious variable project_time which is on the x-axis. binwidth has been assigned to 0.5, color is bisque3 and also changed the scale of x-axis via. scale_x_continuous function, in which breaks are being used with the gap of 1 from range(1,30), so that our plot can be easily interpreted. Furthermore, in the next layer we have added stat_bin function so that we can show particular counts of projects in a time- period. Finally, a minimal theme has been added to the plot 

projects <- ggplot(raw_df,aes(project_time))+
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, fill = 'bisque3')

projects <- projects + labs(title = 'Completion time of projects', x = 'Completion time( in years)', y = 'Number of projects', caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, 30, by = 1))+
   stat_bin(aes(y=..count..,label=ifelse(..count..==0,"",..count..)), geom="text", vjust=-.5)+
  theme_minimal()
projects

The above graph illustrates how many years a project takes to complete. The x_axis representing the completion time of the projects (in years) and the y_axis shows the Number of projects. We can clearly see that almost 65% of projects’ completion time vary from 3 years to 6 years. There are around 106 projects whose completion time is 5 years. However, only four projects that took less than 4 years to complete and 6 projects took more than 16 years to complete.


Here, we create a boxplot for cost_km_millions continuous variable with the help of boxplot geometry in ggplot2 package, then changed the scale of x_axis via. scale_x_continuous function, in which breaks are being used with the gap of 250 from range(0,4000).Finally, by using theme, in which we have defined y_axis as its density. And used title in the labs function. 

ggplot(raw_df,aes(cost_km_millions))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 4000, by = 250))+
  labs(title = 'Cost per Km of transit projects in millions of USD', x = 'Cost/Km in Millions',y= "Density", caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost")+
  theme_dark()


The above box plot has been created, for analyzing the Cost/km of transit projects in millions of USD ( cost_km_millions). We can see that 50 percentile projects’ cost is from 125 to 250. Approximately 75 % of the cost of the project is under 250 million per km. In addition, 6 projects cost higher than 1250 million per km. Out of them, one project cost is around 4000 million/km.


Since we want to plot for categorical variable, We use bar_geometry in ggplot2 package and defined aesthetics under geom_bar() which is country on x-axis and also assigned country to color also. By assigning country to color, every country will be shown in different colors that helps to visualize clearly.Further, we have defined the width of bar is 0.8 and then used coord_flip(), so that our x-axis and y-axis interchanged positions.Finally, we have use labs() for labeling.In theme, we have also defined y text size, so that it can clearly visualize. 

ggplot(raw_df)+
  geom_bar(aes(country,  color = country), width=0.8)+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = 'Number of projects started in different countries', x = 'Country', y = 'Count',caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost")+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 5))


It can be seen that CN-China is the only country in which more than 250 Transit_projects’ started while, approximately 25 projects accounted for ‘IN’ Country. All other countries’ projects figure is less than 25.

Creating Country List to filter out top 10 countries with highest number of projects. From the transit data set, all the projects that are completed are filttered by filtering the end_year upto 2020. The number of projects in different countries are counted from the filtered data set and top 10 countries are taken and stored in country_list.

country_list <-  raw_df %>%
  filter(end_year <= 2020) %>% 
  count(country)%>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  pull(country)


The code below is for top 10 countries that are taken and filtered from country using country_list. Using ggplot a segment plot layer as well as point plot layer is plotted with global aes x-aixs as country and y-axis as country.For segment plot country is given to xend, 0 to yend and in plot plot layer colour oranger is given for points.The axis are flipped and changed the theme for better view.

raw_df %>%
  filter(country %in% country_list) %>%
  ggplot(aes(country, real_cost, colour = country)) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend=country, yend=0))+
  geom_point( size=2, color="orange") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("")+
  labs(title = "Project costs for top 10 countries with maximum number of projects.",
       x = "Country",
       y = "Real cost in Millions of USD",caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost")


This plot depicts the real cost in millions( USD) for the top 10 countries having a maximum number of projects. The x-axis has a real_cost in millions (USD) and the y-axis has the top 10 countries with the highest number of projects.From the plot, we can see that FR(France) has to spend a maximum amount of cost that should be more than 45000 USD, followed by SA(South Africa) and IN(India) spending around 38000 USD and 32000 USD respectively.


Using ggplot globally defined the aes x-axis as length, y-axis as real_cost, assigned colour to stations and size to tunnel. Added geom_point layer as well as geom_smooth layer for better understanding of the trend.

raw_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=length,y=real_cost,colour=stations,size=tunnel,na.rm=TRUE))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(title = "Plot showing the relation between Length, Stations and Tunnel with Real cost.",
       x = 'Length',
       y = 'Real Cost in Millions USD',caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost")


The plot shows the relationship between length, stations and tunnel with real cost. The x-axis has length whereas, the y-axis shows the real cost in millions(USD).
-From the plot, we can infer the bellow points
-As the length increases real cost also increases
-As the number of stations increases real cost increases
-As the number of tunnels increases real cost increases
Length, stations and tunnels are directly proportional to the real cost.


Filtered the dataset taking only the top 10 countries with maximum number of projects. Defined the aes globally with x-axis as cost and y-axis as real cost and assigned colour to PPP_rate then added geom_point layer. Rescaled the x and y axis using xlim and ylim.

raw_df %>%
  filter(country %in% country_list) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=cost,y=real_cost,colour=ppp_rate))+
  geom_point()+
  xlim(0,10000)+
  ylim(0,10000)+
  labs(title = "Plot showing the relation between Cost and Real cost in USD with  PPP rate.",
       x = 'Cost in country currency',
       y = 'Real cost in USD',caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost")


The plot shows the relation between cost, PPP rate and real cost.We can see that countries with higher PPP rate have real cost more than the cost in their currency whereas, countries with less PPP rate has real cost less than their currency cost.

Using the China_cities data added a geom_point layer with aes x-axis as project time, y-axis as length, assigned colour to source1 and size to stations.Then added a geom_smooth layer with aes as project_time and length.After which facet is added for cities and stored these data in Completion_data.

Completion_data <- ggplot( data = China_cities) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(project_time,length,colour=stations)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(project_time,length))+
  facet_wrap( ~city)
Completion_data <- Completion_data + 
  labs(title = 'Project completion time for 6 cities of China', x = 'Completion time( in years)',y ='Length of the proposed projects(in Km )',caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost") 

Completion_data


This plot explains the relationship between the length of the Infrastructure Project and the years took to complete in 6 cities of China that are: Xi’an, Wuhan, Shanghai, Beijing, Shenzhen, Changsha. Length on the y-axis refers to the proposed project distance expressed in kilometres.Project time on the x-axis refers to the number of years taken to complete the project from the start date to the end date and expressed in years.The Graph mainly explains the trend of the project progress for all cities, as from the smooth line, we can observe that completion time is increasing when the length of the project increases.
The size of the scatter plot also refers to the number of stations that the particular project has and it is measured on a scale of 10 to 30 stations dividing equally between 3 sizes. It is evident that city Xi’an and Changsha has the less number of projects and all those projects are completed in less than 5 years.China has planned to build more infrastructure projects in cities like Beijing and Shanghai when compared to the rest of the four cities highlighted in this plot.



Considering top 6 countries.

country_list_six <- transit_cost %>% 
  count(country)%>% 
  top_n(6) %>% pull(country)


The code contains a plot of a list of countries in country_plot by filtering the data set (transit_cost) concerning the list of top 6 countries. We use ggplot and map x to end_ year, y to real_cost and provide colour to the country. By doing this we can get a timeline of each project completion and the real cost associated with it. We choose to add aesthetics geom_point and facet_wrap as we have the top 6 countries.

country_plot<- transit_cost %>% 
  filter(country %in% country_list_six) %>%  
  ggplot(aes(x= end_year, y= real_cost, color=country)) +  
    geom_point()+ facet_wrap(~country, nrow=3)+
    labs(title = "Real cost by end of the project of top 6 countries" , subtitle = "Data also contains maximum number of completed Projects",
       x = 'End year(year)',
       y = 'Real cost in USD',
       caption = "Data source: Transit_Cost")


Animating the plot by taking top 6 countries.

animate_plot <- country_plot + geom_point(aes(group = seq_along(year))) +   transition_reveal(year)
animate_plot

This plot has the comparison of real cost on the y-axis for the top 6 countries corresponding to the years on the x-axis. By this plot, we can see that China, India and France have a significant increase in the real cost as well as several projects from the year 2020 onwards.We can also see a similar pattern in JP(Japan), TR(Turkey) and ES( Spain) as the number of completed projects have increased from the year 2010. The plot also indicates an increasing PPP rate of the countries with respect to years progression.

Answers to questions

-In what ways do you think data visualization is important to understanding a data set?

Data visualization is important in understanding data set in following ways: The primary objective of data visualization is to provide exploratory data analysis of the dataset to get useful insights and communicate the findings that could be understood better by the target audience. Data visualization helps in identifying the trends, clusters, local and global patterns from the data set which gives more information on how different variables contribute and have dependencies with each other.

Example- Transit_cost data set we observed that there is a correlation between variables(Real Cost and Length)

We are also able to identify inconsistencies and missing values which we can analyse by exploratory data analysis to make the data set more accurate thereby increasing the quality of the data set. An effective data visualization adds meaning to complicated datasets that make the message and depiction more concise and easier to interpret by using suitable visual graphs, maps and charts.

-In what ways do you think data visualization is important to communicating important aspects of a data set?

It is very difficult to comprehend aspects of a data set based on just observations and calculations; however, by data visualization we are able to identify and explore correlation, relationships, and the significance of variables. Visual interpretation is way better to interpret various factors that influence or affect a scenario. By identifying the important aspects of a data set by data visualization we can make better and prompt decisions, understand key insights, identify areas that need to be worked, find root cause to solve a problem and provide a useful conclusion that can be used for developing strategies. Data visualization must tell a story behind the dataset, it means that a good visualization contains all the valuable information without clustering and hoarding with information and is able to explain what the data set is intended for.

-What role does your integrity as an analyst play when creating a data visualization for communicating results to others?

As an analyst the primary goal is to visualize the data accurately without distorting facts. The focus should be on the data as provided and not correlate it with data that is out of context. An Analyst should adhere to concise visualization with possible interactive representation of data which should be clear, detailed and labelled correctly in order to avoid graphical distortion and ambiguity. The role of an analyst is to provide a visualization that can be interpreted by everyone without complexities in interpretation. Data visualization should use all the necessary variables to represent the correct meaning behind the data.

-How many variables do you think you can successfully represent in a visualization? What happens when you exceed this number?

A successful visualization is about showing the connection between data which would be too complex to be explained and interpreted by words. A good data visualization will present the data which will be easy for the audience to comprehend and draw an outcome from the dataset. According to Edward Tufte’s Six Principles of Graphical Integrity, The number of information-carrying (variable) dimensions depicted should not exceed the number of dimensions in the data.

There should be at least 4 variables in order to convey a clear data visualization however, the number of variables are also dependent on the type of plot being used. Ideal visualization is dependent on comparison such as numeric to numeric (scatterplot), Categorical to numeric( multiple histogram) or categorical to categorical( bar plot)

We should not exceed the number of variables in the visualization to maximum as it will increase the complexities in understanding and following the visualization for the audience. This not only helps in a clear visualization but also avoids scenarios of an overplotting.
